Storage class, dynamic provisioning.

A storage class is the recipe for, how do you make a new disk. When a claim names a storage class, the cluster follows that recipe to provision a fresh volume on demand. Let us go through the fields that matter day to day.

The provisioner names which storage driver to use. The cluster has these drivers installed, and you reference them by name. There is a cloud block storage driver for each major cloud, a network file share driver, and a simple local path driver on kind.

The parameters are driver specific. A cloud block driver takes things like the disk type and the requested input output operations per second. A file share driver takes the server and the share path.

The reclaim policy decides what happens to the disk when the claim is deleted, which we cover next. It is almost always delete for a dynamically provisioned class, and retain for hand curated ones.

The volume binding mode is an important one. Immediate, the default, picks or creates a volume the moment the claim is created. Wait for first consumer holds off until a pod actually schedules, then provisions the disk in that pod's zone. You want wait for first consumer whenever storage is zonal, otherwise you risk creating a disk in one zone and then scheduling the pod in another, where it cannot attach.

And allow volume expansion controls whether a claim using this class can be resized later.

You can also mark one storage class as the default. Then any claim that does not name a class gets the default, which keeps everyday manifests short.
